Solution:
Heat of vaporization is

$$
L=T \Delta S=540 \mathrm{cal} / \mathrm{g} .
$$From $d H=T d S+V d p$, we get

$$
H_{\text {water }}=H_{\text {steam }}-T \Delta S=100 \mathrm{cal} / \mathrm{g} \text {. }
$$Since $G=H-T S$,

$$
G_{\text {water }}=H_{\text {water }}-T S_{\text {water }}=-16 \mathrm{cal} / \mathrm{g} \text {, }
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& G_{\text {steam }}=H_{\text {steam }}-T S_{\text {steam }}=-16 \mathrm{cal} / \mathrm{g} \text {, }
\end{aligned}
$$

The energy eigenvalues are given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\varepsilon &=\frac{h^{2}}{2 m L^{2}}\left(n_{x}^{2}+n_{y}^{2}+n_{z}^{2}\right), \\
&=\frac{1}{2 M}\left(p_{x}^{2}+p_{y}^{2}+p_{z}^{2}\right)=\frac{p^{2}}{2 M},
\end{aligned}
$$

where $n_{x}, n_{y}, n_{z}=0, \pm 1, \ldots$.

The energy levels can be thought of as quasi-continuous, so that the number of quantum states in the range $p \rightarrow p+d p$ is $\frac{4 \pi V}{h^{3}} p^{2} d p$, whence the number of states in the energy interval $\varepsilon \rightarrow \varepsilon+d \varepsilon$ is $\frac{2 \pi V}{h^{3}}(2 M)^{3 / 2} \sqrt{\varepsilon} d \varepsilon$. Hence

$$
\begin{aligned}
z &=\int_{0}^{\infty} \frac{2 \pi V}{h^{3}}(2 M)^{3 / 2} \varepsilon^{1 / 2} e^{-\beta \varepsilon} d \varepsilon \\
&=\frac{V}{h^{3}}\left(\frac{M k T}{2 \pi}\right)^{3 / 2} \cdot\left(4 \pi^{2}\right)^{3 / 2}=\frac{8 \pi^{3} V}{h^{3}} \cdot n_{q}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $n_{q}=\left(\frac{M k T}{2 \pi}\right)^{3 / 2}$ is the average number of quantum states in unit volume.

